<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> in a fashion • in the fashion</xh5><p> <i>in a fashion—</i>1. <i>(also: after a fashion)</i> to a certain extent but not very satisfactorily: I kept puffing at it [trombone] until I could play, <u>in a fashion</u>, the little Jim Robinson solo. 2. in the way specified: Nor did he fail to condemn wrong doing <u>in a fashion</u> which Scotch folk call teethy.</p><p> <i>in the fashion</i>— = in a fashion 2: Mrs. Rauscher mistook the meaning of the question and responded <u>in the fashion</u> she did to her own embarrassment.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>in fashion</b>—popular; fashionable: This writer was <u>in fashion</u> at the beginning of the century.</p> </entry>
